    <stitle>VT-365 Diesel Engine Diagnostics (2002) - ELECTRONIC CONTROL SYSTEMS DIAGNOSTICS - Circuit Diagnostics -
        Barometric Absolute Pressure (BAP) Sensor
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="3">
        <title>Barometric Absolute Pressure (BAP) Sensor</title>
        <svcprocinfo>
            <figure id="f24007" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic id="d3347" filename="../figd33/d3347.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="432px"/>
                <caption>Function Diagram for the Barometric Absolute Pressure (BAP) Sensor</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>The Function Diagram for the BAP sensor includes the following:</para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Barometric Absolute Pressure (BAP) sensor</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Electronic Control Module (ECM)</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Injection Driver Module (IDM)</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Fuel injector</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>ENGINE lamp (amber)</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <para>
                <title>Function</title>
            </para>
            <para>The BAP sensor is a cab mounted variable capacitance sensor. The ECM supplies a 5V reference signal
                which the BAP sensor uses to produce a linear analog voltage signal that indicates pressure.
            </para>
            <para>The primary function of the BAP sensor is to provide a feedback signal to the ECM to adjust timing and
                fuel quantity. The ECM also uses the BAP signal to determine altitude to adjust glow plug on-time,
                control EGR and VGT.
            </para>
        </svcprocinfo>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>BAP Circuit Operation</title>
            <figure id="f24007" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic id="d3348" filename="../figd33/d3348.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="432px"/>
                <caption>BAP Circuit Diagram</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>The BAP sensor is supplied with a 5V regulated signal voltage by the ECM from the ECM chassis
                connector terminal X4-4 to BAP connector terminal 2. The BAP sensor returns a variable voltage signal
                (representing atmospheric pressure) from BAP connector terminal 3 to ECM at terminal X3-24. The BAP
                sensor is grounded from the BAP connector terminal 1 to the ECM signal ground terminal X4-24.
            </para>
            <para>
                <title>Fault Detection / Management</title>
            </para>
            <para>When the ECM detects the BAP voltage signal out of range high or low, the ECM will ignore the BAP
                signal and use the Manifold Absolute Pressure (MAP) signal generated at low idle as an indication of
                barometric pressure. When a MAP fault is detected, the BAP signal will default to barometric pressure at
                sea level, 100.24 kPa (29.6 in Hg).
            </para>
            <para>
                <title>BAP Diagnostic Trouble Codes (DTCs)</title>
            </para>
            <para>DTCs are read using the Electronic Service Tool (EST) or by counting the flashes from the amber and
                red ENGINE lamp.
            </para>
            <verbatim id="f240dtc151">
                <line>
                    <emph type="bold">DTC 151</emph>
                </line>
                <line>
                    <emph type="bold">Out of range high</emph>
                </line>
            </verbatim>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>DTC 151 is set when the BAP signal is greater than 4.95V for more than .5 second.</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>DTC 151 can be set when the signal circuit is shorted to V
                        <subscript>REF</subscript>
                        or B+. A defective BAP sensor can set DTC 151.
                    </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>When DTC 151 is active the amber ENGINE lamp is illuminated.</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>The ECM monitors voltage on V
                        <subscript>REF</subscript>
                        A and will adjust signal values for the sensors that use V
                        <subscript>REF</subscript>
                        A for operation. If a sensor or circuit pulls V
                        <subscript>REF</subscript>
                        lower than 5V, the ECM may set out of range high DTCs for the sensors that operate on V
                        <subscript>REF</subscript>
                        B (APS, BAP, B+, and VSS).
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <verbatim id="f240dtc152">
                <line>
                    <emph type="bold">DTC 152</emph>
                </line>
                <line>
                    <emph type="bold">Out of range low</emph>
                </line>
            </verbatim>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>DTC 152 is set when the BAP signal is less than 1.0V for more than .5 second.</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>DTC 152 can be set when the signal circuit is shorted to ground or open. If the V
                        <subscript>REF</subscript>
                        is shorted to ground, DTC 152 can be set. A defective BAP sensor can set DTC 152.
                    </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>When DTC 152 is active the amber ENGINE lamp is illuminated.</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <para>
                <title>Tools</title>
            </para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Electronic Service Tool (EST) with Master Diagnostics software</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>International&#174; EZ-Tech Interface Cable</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Digital Multimeter (DMM)</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Breakout box</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
        </svcsubproc>
